    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-09-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-09-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="237"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d237">
                <head>237. Memorandum From the Assistant Secretary of Defense for International
                    Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_NGW1" type="from">Nutter</persName>) to
                    the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff (<persName corresp="#p_MTH1" type="to"
                        >Moorer</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d237fn1">Source:
                        Washington National Records Center, <gloss target="#t_OASD1"
                            >OASD</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_ISA1">ISA</gloss> Files: <gloss
                            target="#t_FRC1">FRC</gloss> 330–74–83, 384 Jan–1971. Secret. For text
                        of the August 5 draft convention, see <ref target="#d235">Document
                        235</ref>.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d237fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_NGW1">Nutter</persName> forwarded draft instructions
                        to Geneva concerning the draft Biological Weapons Convention and asked for
                            <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>’s comments.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1971-09-13"
                        >September 13, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT:</head>
                    <item>Negotiation of <gloss target="#t_BW1">BW</gloss> Convention</item>
                </list>
                <p>I would like to have the views of the Joint Chiefs of Staff on the attached draft
                    message of instruction to the United States delegation at the Conference of the
                    Committee on Disarmament in Geneva concerning the draft Bacteriological Warfare
                    Convention. A reply is requested by 17 September, if possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_NGW1">G. Warren Nutter</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <pb facs="d237-02" n="2" xml:id="d237-02"/>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <head>Attachment<lb/>Draft Telegram From the Department of State to the Mission
                        in Geneva</head>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1971-09-13">undated</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <list type="subject">
                        <head>SUBJECT:</head>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_CCD1">CCD</gloss>: Negotiation of <gloss
                                target="#t_BW1">BW</gloss> Convention</item>
                    </list>
                    <list type="references">
                        <head>REF:</head>
                        <item>A. Geneva 3844</item>
                        <item>B. Geneva 3849</item>
                        <item>C. Geneva 3850</item>
                        <item>D. Geneva 3851</item>
                        <item>E. Geneva 3852</item>
                    </list>
                    <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>We are prepared to accept changes in text of August 5 draft convention
                            as reported reftels.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Text of <gloss target="#t_BW1">BW</gloss> convention as sent reftel B
                            represents achievement of main US objective: development, production and
                            stockpiling of <gloss target="#t_BW1">BW</gloss>, already renounced
                            unilaterally by <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss>, would be prohibited
                            by treaty. Moreover, the two major <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>
                            concerns in negotiating the treaty are met: 1) draft does not affect
                                <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> position on Geneva Protocol and 2)
                            commitment to further negotiations on chemical weapons prohibitions does
                            not prejudge outcome of such negotiations.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>We appreciate efforts of Del to arrive at draft which would appear
                            generally acceptable at <gloss target="#t_CCD1">CCD</gloss> and at
                                <gloss target="#t_UNGA1">UNGA</gloss>. <pb facs="d237-03" n="3"
                                xml:id="d237-03"/> We believe some additions will be particularly
                            acceptable to our allies (e.g., additions to Articles I and V) while new
                            language proposed by non-aligned for preamble and operative Articles
                            VIII and IX should increase support for Convention.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>
                            <p>a. We favor inclusion of optional article on <gloss target="#t_BW1"
                                    >BW</gloss> assistance (para 13, reftel D) if, in light of
                                further consultations with Sovs and other dels, <gloss
                                    target="#t_US1">US</gloss> del believe this would enhance
                                overall support for treaty.</p>
                            <p>b. We consider preambular para 4 of proposed text an improvement, but
                                we continue to be able to accept August 5 version.</p>
                            <p>C. If in Del’s judgment it would significantly increase non-aligned
                                backing for <gloss target="#t_BW1">BW</gloss> convention you
                                authorized insert “comprehensive” in preambular para of proposed
                                text (para 7, reftel C).</p>
                        </item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>FOR USNATO, ALL <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> CAPITALS AND
                            EMBASSY TOKYO: Consultations with our <gloss target="#t_NATO1"
                                >NATO</gloss> allies and Japan on new language should begin soonest.
                            Instructions follow septel.</item>
                    </list>
                    <p>END</p>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
